## Installation

```bash
# Install uv (if needed)
curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh

# Clone and install
git clone https://github.com/{{ github_username }}/{{ project_slug }}.git
cd {{ project_slug }}
uv sync --all-groups
```

## Development

{% if task_runner == "just" or task_runner == "both" %}
This project uses [Just](https://github.com/casey/just) as the task runner.

```bash
just              # list all available commands
just install      # install all dependencies
just test         # run tests
just lint         # format + lint + type-check (auto-fix)
just check        # verify without modifying (CI equivalent)
just audit        # dependency security audit
```

To install Just: `cargo install just` or see [other install methods](https://github.com/casey/just#installation).

{% endif %}
{% if task_runner == "make" or task_runner == "both" %}
```bash
make help         # list all commands
make install      # install dependencies
make test         # run tests
make lint         # check code
make format       # format code
```

{% endif %}

Without a task runner, equivalent commands:

```bash
uv sync --all-groups                                 # install
uv run pytest --cov                                  # test
uv run ruff format src/ tests/                       # format
uv run ruff check --fix src/ tests/                  # lint
uv run ty check src/                                 # type-check
uv run pip-audit                                     # audit
```

{% if use_docker %}
## Docker

For reproducible builds, generate and commit `uv.lock` before the first `docker build`:

```bash
# 1. Generate the lockfile (once, or after dependency changes)
uv sync
git add uv.lock && git commit -m "chore: add lockfile"

# 2. Build images
docker build -t {{ project_slug }}:latest --target prod .
docker build -t {{ project_slug }}:dev --target dev .

# 3. Run the production container
docker run --rm {{ project_slug }}:latest

# 4. Run the development container (interactive shell)
docker run --rm -it {{ project_slug }}:dev
```
{% endif %}

{% if use_data %}
## Data

The `data/` directory is tracked with **Git LFS**. Install Git LFS on your machine:

```bash
git lfs install   # once per machine
git clone ...     # LFS files are fetched on clone
```

Default tracked formats are common data types (CSV, Parquet, NPY, ML models,
images, archives). To track additional formats for your domain, edit
`.gitattributes`:

```bash
# Example for scientific formats
*.h5 filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
*.tif filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
```

{% endif %}

{% if use_pypi_publish %}
## Publishing to PyPI

This project uses [PyPI Trusted Publishing](https://docs.pypi.org/trusted-publishers/)
(OIDC) — no API token to manage.

**One-time setup**:

1. Configure the project on PyPI: https://pypi.org/manage/account/publishing/
2. Set:
   - Repository owner: `{{ github_username }}`
   - Repository name: `{{ project_slug }}`
   - Workflow file: `publish.yml`
   - Environment: `pypi`
3. Create the `pypi` environment in GitHub: Settings → Environments → New environment

**Publish a release**: create a GitHub Release with tag `vX.Y.Z`. The `publish.yml`
workflow runs automatically.

{% endif %}

